        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 299. <placeName type="findspot">Knockboy</placeName> 
                     VIII</name>, Co. <placeName type="county">Waterford</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WA013-034015-"
                >WA013-034015-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Ecclesiastical (probably early)</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>The parish church of Seskinan (WA013-034001-) was probably built on the site of an earlier church. 
                        There were traces of an ecclesiastical enclosure in the field to the S and within the graveyard (<ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1869"><bibl><author>Brash</author>
                            <date when="1869">1868-9</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >127</biblScope></bibl></ref>; <ref type="bibliog" target="#POW1898"><bibl><author>Power</author>
                                    <date when="1898">1898</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >84</biblScope></bibl></ref>), 
                        but this is no longer evident. There is also the site of Toberatemple Well (WA013-032001-) c. 250m to the W (<ref type="bibliog" target="#POW1898"><bibl><author>Power</author>
                            <date when="1898">1898</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >83</biblScope></bibl></ref>).
                        The church is an undifferentiated structure (int. dims. 22.2m E-W; 7.55m N-S) surviving complete (H of long walls c. 2.1-2.5m) with quoins 
                        and a double bellcote (now damaged) over the W gable. There are pointed doorways towards the W end of the N and S walls, with a stoup inside 
                        the S doorway and an aumbry at the E end of the S wall. Two ogee-headed windows, one above the other, are in the W gable, with another in the 
                        E wall, and there are two simple lights towards the E end of the long walls. All the embrasures are lintelled internally except the E window 
                        which has a flat arch of dressed voussoirs and ingoings. The square base of a font (WA013-034004-) is also located within the church (<ref type="bibliog" target="#POW1898"><bibl><author>Power</author>
                            <date when="1898">1898</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >83</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p>
                    <p>All of the lintels, except one over the N doorway, have ogham inscriptions (<ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1869"><bibl><author>Brash</author>
                        <date when="1869">1868-9</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >118-30</biblScope></bibl></ref>; <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                            ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >286-9</biblScope></bibl></ref>), and a seventh ogham stone 
                        is standing in the NW corner of the church. An eighth ogham stone, said to have also originated here, was recorded by <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1907"
                            ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                (<date when="1907">1907</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >213</biblScope></bibl></ref>; <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                        ><bibl>
                                            <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                >289</biblScope></bibl></ref>; see also <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                                                    <date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                        >270</biblScope></bibl></ref> and <ref type="bibliog" target="#RED1886"><bibl><author>Redmond</author> 
                                                            <date when="1886">1885-6</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                                >418-9</biblScope></bibl></ref>) 
                        at Salterbridge House, near Cappoquin prior to 1907 (photograph from <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1907"
                            ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                <date when="1907">1907</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >212</biblScope></bibl></ref>) but it was missing when he returned in 1940.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p> 
                        <rs type="material"/>'Slab of old red sandstone', 
                        <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">0.66</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.28</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.10</measure>m
                            <lb/> (converted from <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                                <date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >270</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                        (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                            >289</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> describes the stone as 'the broken-off top of a pillar-stone'. </rs></p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>The inscription read up-top-down, beginning on the left-hand angle at the broken end. Despite a spall on the face near the top of the stone, the remaining inscription appeared to be in tact                        
                         <ref type="bibliog" target="#RED1886">(<bibl><author>Redmond</author> 
                                    <date when="1886">1885-6</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >418-9</biblScope></bibl></ref>). <q>The prefixed MAQI is purely conjectural: nothing is left of it but the last two vowel-notches</q> <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                            <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                >289</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>  
                <ab>  
                    <lb/><w><supplied reason="lost">MAQ</supplied><unclear reason="damaged">I</unclear></w>
                    <persName><w lemma="MONGEDIAS">MO<unclear reason="incomprehensible">NG</unclear>EDIAS</w></persName>/
                    <w type="formula" lemma="MAQI">MAQI</w>/
                    <persName><w lemma="MUIBITI">MUIBITI</w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
