            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The NG (three scores crossing the stemline diagonally) of MONGEDIAS is the later manuscript value for this consonant. However, as this <q>is not a radical initial in Irish, no more than is the H of <hi rend="italic">hÚath</hi>, 
                        and is not contained in the letter name itself [<hi rend="italic">Gétal</hi>], it cannot be authentic</q> <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >21, 37-8</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. It occurs very rarely in the early monumental inscriptions and its original value remains unclear, although 
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1988"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1988">1988</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >157-9</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> 
                        has suggested a Primitive Irish value /g<hi rend="superscript">w</hi>/.</p></item>
                </list>
                
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Found in 1869 by <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                                (<date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >270</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> 'lying on a low wall in the pleasure ground at the west side' of Salterbridge House 
                            (the residence of the Chearnley Family who were proprietors of the estate, which included the church and graveyard at Knockboy), in the townland of <placeName type="townland">Salterbridge</placeName> and barony of <placeName
                                type="barony"> Coshmore and Coshbride</placeName>. Reported to <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                    (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >289</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> by Richard Chearnley (Salterbridge, proprietor of estate) to have come from Seskinan church.
                            </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation"></rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">The stone was reported lost by 1940 when <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >289</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> revisited Salterbridge. The last known location of this stone
                            may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WA021-011----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref> (GPS coordinates
                            <geo> -7.881039, 52.148923</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>This ogham stone appears to have been first noticed by Brash in 1869 <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879">(<bibl><date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                        >270</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. Redmond recorded and sketched the stone in 1885 <ref type="bibliog" target="#RED1886">(<bibl><date when="1886">1885-6</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >418-9</biblScope></bibl></ref>) and a description with photograph appeared in Macalister's <hi rend="italic">Studies in Irish
                                    Epigraphy</hi> in <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1907"
                                        ><bibl><date when="1907">1907</date> (<biblScope type="pp"
                                                >213</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
            </div>
